\fB/etc/smartmontools/smartd.conf\fP is tha configuration file fo' tha \fBsmartd\fP
daemon.

If tha configuration file \fB/etc/smartmontools/smartd.conf\fP is present,
\fBsmartd\fP readz it at startup, before \fBfork\fP(2)in tha fuck into the
background. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! If \fBsmartd\fP subsequently receives a \fBHUP\fP signal,
it will then re-read tha configuration file.  If \fBsmartd\fP is
runnin up in debug mode, then a \fBINT\fP signal will also make it
re-read tha configuration file. This signal can be generated by typing
\fB\<CONTROL-C\>\fP up in tha terminal window where \fBsmartd\fP is
running.

In tha absence of a cold-ass lil configuration file
\fBsmartd\fP will try ta open all available devices
(see \fBsmartd\fP(8) playa page).
A configuration file wit a single line \fB\'DEVICESCAN \-a'\fP
would have tha same effect.

This can be buggin if you have a ATA or SCSI thang dat hangs or
misbehaves when receivin SMART commands.  Even if dis causes no
problems, you may be annoyed by tha strang of error log lyrics bout devices
that can\'t be opened.

One can avoid dis problem, n' bust mo' control over tha types of
events monitored by
\fBsmartd\fP,
by rockin tha configuration file
.B /etc/smartmontools/smartd.conf.
This file gotz nuff a list of devices ta monitor, wit one thang per
line.  An example file is included wit the
.B smartmontools
distribution. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. Yo ass will find dis sample configuration file in
\fB/usr/share/doc/smartmontools/\fP. For security, tha configuration file
should not be writable by mah playas but root. Da syntax of tha file be as
bigs up:
.IP \(bu 4
There should be one thang listed per line, although you may have
lines dat is entirely comments or white space.
.IP \(bu 4
Any text followin a hash sign \'#\' n' up ta tha end of tha line is
taken ta be a cold-ass lil comment, n' ignored.
.IP \(bu 4
Lines may be continued by rockin a funky-ass backslash \'\e\' as tha last
non-whitespace or non-comment item on a line.
.IP \(bu 4
Note: a line whose first characta be a hash sign \'#\' is treated as
a white-space blank line, \fBnot\fP as a non-existent line, n' will
\fBend\fP a cold-ass lil continuation line.
.PP 0
.fi
Here be a example configuration file.  It\z fo' illustratizzle purposes
only; please don\'t copy it onto yo' system without readin ta tha end
of the
.B DIRECTIVES
Section below!

