.TP
.B \-n POWERMODE[,N][,q]
[ATA only] This \'nocheck\' Directizzle is used ta prevent a gangbangin' finger-lickin' disk from
bein spun-up when it is periodically polled by \fBsmartd\fP.

ATA disks have five different juice states. In order of increasing
power consumption they are: \'OFF\', \'SLEEP\', \'STANDBY\', \'IDLE\',
and \'ACTIVE\'.  Typically up in tha OFF, SLEEP, n' STANDBY modes the
disk\z plattas is not spinning. But usually, up in response ta SMART
commandz issued by \fBsmartd\fP, tha disk plattas is spun up.  So if
this option aint used, then a gangbangin' finger-lickin' disk which is up in a low-power mode may
be spun up n' put tha fuck into a higher-power mode when it is periodically
polled by \fBsmartd\fP.

Note dat if tha disk is up in SLEEP mode when \fBsmartd\fP is started,
then it won't respond ta \fBsmartd\fP commands, n' so tha disk won't
be registered as a thang fo' \fBsmartd\fP ta monitor. Shiiit, dis aint no joke. If a gangbangin' finger-lickin' disk is in
any other low-power mode, then tha commandz issued by \fBsmartd\fP to
regista tha disk will probably cause it ta spin-up.

Da \'\fB\-n\fP\' (nocheck) Directizzle specifies if \fBsmartd\fP\'s
periodic checks should still be carried up when tha thang is up in a
low-power mode.  It may be used ta prevent a gangbangin' finger-lickin' disk from bein spun-up
by periodic \fBsmartd\fP polling.  Da allowed jointz of POWERMODE
are:

.I never
\- \fBsmartd\fP will poll (check) tha thang regardless of its power
mode. This may cause a gangbangin' finger-lickin' disk which is spun-down ta be spun-up when
\fBsmartd\fP checks dat shit.  This is tha default behavior if tha '\-n'
Directizzle aint given.

.I chill
\- check tha thang unless it is up in SLEEP mode.

.I standby
\- check tha thang unless it is up in SLEEP or STANDBY mode.  In
these modes most disks is not spinning, so if you wanna prevent
a laptop disk from spinnin up each time dat \fBsmartd\fP polls,
this is probably what tha fuck you want.

.I idle
\- check tha thang unless it is up in SLEEP, STANDBY or IDLE mode.
In tha IDLE state, most disks is still spinning, so dis is probably
not what tha fuck you want.

